               <interp inst="t18621027-1132" type="date" value="18621027"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18621027-1132-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1132-18621027 t18621027-1132-offence-1 t18621027-1132-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1132. <persName id="def1-1132-18621027" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1132-18621027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1132-18621027" type="age" value="51"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1132-18621027" type="surname" value="EDWARDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1132-18621027" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOSEPH EDWARDS</hi> (51)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18621027-1132-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18621027-1132-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18621027-1132-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp>, Unlawfully obtaining, by false pre<lb></lb>tences, 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., from <persName id="t18621027-name-562" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-562" type="surname" value="WORSFOLD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-562" type="given" value="JOSEPH LEWIS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18621027-1132-offence-1 t18621027-name-562"></join>Joseph Lewis Worsfold</persName>, 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., from <persName id="t18621027-name-563" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-563" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-563" type="surname" value="FORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-563" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18621027-1132-offence-1 t18621027-name-563"></join>John Ford</persName>, and 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., from <persName id="t18621027-name-564" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-564" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-564" type="surname" value="MATTHAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-564" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18621027-1132-offence-1 t18621027-name-564"></join>William Henry Matthams</persName>, with intent to defraud.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KEMP</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-565" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-565" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-565" type="surname" value="FORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-565" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FORD</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 34, Crucifix-lane, Bermondsey, and am in the employ of Mr. William Bryer, a bone and oil merchant—on 19th September the prisoner came there and said, "I have a quantity of bones, refuse, and glue pieces, at the Nine Elms station, in three trucks"—I was not three when my master purchased them—I heard him say there was 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., charges on them to be paid, and he asked my master to advance the money to pay the charges—my master handed the money to me, and I went with the prisoner to the Nine Elms station in the cart—he got out at the station, went into the office and came out again, and said, "You give me the 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and I will go and pay the charges"—I gave him the 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and he said, "Draw your horse over there," directing me across the road—I waited some time there, but did not see him again on that day; he never came—I saw him some days after<lb></lb>wards at the same station, coming out of a public-house—I went and took hold of him, and asked him whether he knew me—he said, "No"—I said, "Don't you recollect taking 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., from me?"—he said, "No"—I then fol<lb></lb>lowed him for about a mile, into Battersea-fields, and then laid hold of him, and gave him into the custody of a policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Was there any other person in the counting-house besides yourself, me, as you say, and the clerk? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not at the time—I did not take hold of you at the railway-station: I went up to you and then fol<lb></lb>lowed you.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-566" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-566" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-566" type="surname" value="MILLS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-566" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MILLS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am manager to Mr. Bryer—I saw the prisoner at our office on 19th, about half-past 8 in the morning—he said he had brought up between five and six tons of bones, refuse, and glue pieces by the railway—</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186210270182"></xptr>
               <p>he said the charges were unpaid, and he requested me to give the man the money to pay them, which I did 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.,—I asked him what his name was—he said, "Crockford, Buckland, Hampshire."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you lend the money to pay the charges on these goods? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At your request, I gave the man 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., to pay the charges, and sent him with you to the Nine Elms station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I deny being in the counting-house at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-567" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-567" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-567" type="surname" value="MATTHAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-567" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>WILLIAM HENRY MATTHAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Southampton-street, Camberwell, and am a whip-maker—on 24th September the prisoner came to me and offered me this sample of grease (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>), saying there were twenty-four casks lying at the Nine Elms station—he asked me 31<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., a cwt. for it, and I bought it—he said there would be charges to pay; would we pay them, or deduct it from the amount—he did not say what amount—I gave my carman 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.,—I am quite certain the prisoner is the man who came.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Was there anyone else there at the time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; several persons about—the charges were to be paid out of the bulk of the money for the goods.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-568" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-568" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-568" type="surname" value="CALLUM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-568" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD CALLUM</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 2, Havil-street, Camberwell, and am carman to the last witness—on 24th September I saw the prisoner at my master's premises—my master gave me 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., to pay the charges on some grease at the Nine Elms station—I drove the prisoner there in the cart—he went into the booking-office and came out again with a paper in his hand—he said he had found the number and the truck, and they were down on the mid-line—he then said he would go and see what the charges came to—he went in, came out again, and said, "They come to 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—I gave him three sovereigns and a half-crown, and he went away—he went down on one side of the trucks and I went the other—he said he would go and fetch the porter who was to deliver the grease—he went away, and I never saw him again till I saw him at the Police-court—I am quite positive he is the man—I could swear to him from a hundred.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you see anything of the sample? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; you par<lb></lb>ticularly requested my master to take care of the empty casks, and he said, "I will guarantee they shall be quite safe"—you also said, going along, there were twenty-four casks, and that I could draw them away in three loads.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-569" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-569" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-569" type="surname" value="WORSFOLD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-569" type="given" value="JOSEPH LEWIS"></interp>JOSEPH LEWIS WORSFOLD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a butcher, at Fulham—on Saturday, 13th September, the prisoner came to my house and showed me a sample of grease in a box, and said he had got fourteen casks lying at the South Western Railway station, which he wanted to dispose of—I asked him about it—he gave satisfactory answers, and I agreed to buy it—he asked me if I could fetch them then—I said, "No; it was no good to go then, because the railway would be closed "—I saw no more of him till Monday morning, at 6 o'clock—I saw him go by my window—my man came to me about two minutes afterwards and I gave him 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., to pay the railway charges on the goods—my man is here; his name is Henry Chambers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> You are mistaken in the identity of the man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I could swear to you in a thousand—my window was shut down when I saw you on the Monday morning; the shutters were open—there were no curtains—I advanced the money to my man to advance to you.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-570" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-570" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-570" type="surname" value="CHAMBERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-570" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY CHAMBERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of the last witness—on Monday morning the prisoner came to me, and asked if my master was up, and told me to go up, and ask him if he would let him have 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., or 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., to pay the charges on fourteen casks of grease—he gave me 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and I went with the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186210270183"></xptr>
               <p>prisoner to the railway station, under my master's direction—I gave the prisoner the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., directly I came down, in my master's yard—we went to the station—he told me to wait outside, and he would go and pay the charges—he went, and then came over to where I was standing with my cart, and said he would go and fetch one of the porters—he went away—I waited there from 7 o'clock till 10, and he did not come back—I did not get the money back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Are you certain that I am the man who asked you to ask your master for the loan? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I am.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-571" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-571" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-571" type="surname" value="SHERLOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-571" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS SHERLOCK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a porter at the Nine Elms station—I have seen the prisoner once on the premises—on 14th September I was spoken to by the witness Chambers—there were not fourteen casks of grease at the station then—I made inquiries from what he said to me, and there were no casks of grease at all there—I was also spoken to by Callum on 24th September—I made inquiries—there were no casks of fat there then—I also had a conversation with Ford—there were no casks for delivery at that time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> On either of those three occasions, did you see me with either of those witnesses at the railway station? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-572" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-572" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-572" type="surname" value="BAMFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-572" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BAMFORD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, V</hi> 332). The prisoner was given into my custody on 24th September by Ford—Ford asked him if he knew him, and he said, "No, I do not"—he was searched at the station, and 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>, two sample boxes of grease, a knife, and the top of an umbrella, found on him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18621027-name-573" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-573" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-573" type="surname" value="SHEPPARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-name-573" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN SHEPPARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am head porter at the Nine Elms goods station—there was no grease, or bones, or glue, there for delivery about 15th, 19th, or 24th, that I am aware of—I think I should have known if there was—I saw the prisoner there on 24th, to the best of my belief—I am not in a position to swear he is the party—he came and asked me about some empty casks from Portsmouth which ought to have arrived two months previous—I examined the books, and made inquiries of the clerk respecting them—he did not ask me anything about any fat—I could learn nothing about the empty casks.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you ever see me present an order for goods at the station? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, not to the best of my belief—I asked, before the Magis<lb></lb>trate, that your cap should be put on—I did not then swear to you—I said, to the best of my belief, you were the man; I could not swear.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I never received a farthing from either of these pro<lb></lb>secutors. If I did receive the money, there is no embezzlement whatever in it. I can assure you I am innocent of the charge preferred against me; I did not receive one single fraction of the money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18621027-1132-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-1132-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-1132-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>.**</hi>—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18621027-1132-punishment-102" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18621027-1132-punishment-102" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18621027-1132-punishment-102" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="penalServitude"></interp>
                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1132-18621027 t18621027-1132-punishment-102"></join>Three Years' Penal Servitude.</rs>
                  </hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">ADJOURNED TO MONDAY, NOVEMBER</hi> 24<hi rend="smallCaps">TH</hi>, 1862.</p>
